<worksheet label="ws-PA-5-2">
  <page>
    <exploration xml:id="PA-5-2">
      <introduction>
        <p>
    Consider the function <m>A</m> defined by the rule
    <me>
      A(x) = \int_1^x f(t) \, dt
    </me>,
    where <m>f(t) = 4-2t</m>.

    </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-5-2-task-0">
        <statement>
          <p>
          Compute <m>A(1)</m> and <m>A(2)</m> exactly.
        </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer/>
        <solution/>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-5-2-task-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
          Use the First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to find a formula for <m>A(x)</m> that does not involve integrals.
          That is,
          use the first FTC to evaluate <m>\int_1^x (4-2t) \, dt</m>.
        </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer/>
        <solution/>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-5-2-task-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
          Observe that <m>f</m> is a linear function;
          what kind of function is <m>A</m>?
        </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer/>
        <solution/>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-5-2-task-3">
        <statement>
          <p>
          Using the formula you found in (b) that does not involve integrals,
          compute <m>A'(x)</m>.
        </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer/>
        <solution/>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-5-2-task-4">
        <statement>
          <p>
          While we have defined <m>f</m> by the rule <m>f(t) = 4-2t</m>,
          it is equivalent to say that <m>f</m> is given by the rule <m>f(x) = 4 - 2x</m>.
          What do you observe about the relationship between <m>A</m> and <m>f</m>?
        </p>
        </statement>
        <hint/>
        <answer/>
        <solution/>
      </task>
    </exploration>
  </page>
</worksheet>
